         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">154 Collins Street ¶ Hobart Town Feb 22d /69 ¶ Dear Baron Von Mueller ¶  ¶ I beg to claim your kind indulgence for troubling you thus soon again and which I am sure you will extend, as I do so in the ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">69.02.22b</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Samuel Wintle</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Archive box 00327, f. 02657, Melbourne Museum.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">154 Collins Street</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Hobart Town Feb 22d /69</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Baron Von Mueller<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M was not created a Baron until 1871. There seems, however, to have been a misapprehension current in Hobart at the time Wintle wrote this letter that he had already been granted the title; see M to J. Agnew, April 1869 (in this edition as 69-04-00), and J. Agnew to M, 19 April 1969.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I beg to claim your kind indulgence for troubling you thus soon again and which I am sure you will extend, as I do so in the cause of science.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When M was visiting Tasmania in early 1869, Wintle met him and showed him a fossil plant, which M took back to Melbourne in order to obtain an opinion from the palaeontologist Frederick McCoy; subsequently, Wintle sent M further specimens (see M to S. Wintle, 2 February 1869 (in this edition as 69-02-02a)).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have been remarkably successful in discovering fossil flora since my last ascent of Mt Wellington.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Tas.</p>
               </note> Two days after I sent you the vegetable impressions I found a magnificent bed of fossiliferous shale teeming with <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">cryptogamia</hi>
               </seg> and on the same day, in the very heart of the city a slab of clay rock covered with stems of plants — specimens of which I send herewith, in the hope that they may be thought […]<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Paper damaged — corner of sheet missing. All subsequent [...] arise from the same cause.</p>
               </note> your National […] you will be kind enough to submit them to professor McCoy.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to F. McCoy, 28 February 1869 (in this edition as 69-02-28b).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The clay rock formation is exposed in a vertical section by the road side and is built over. It overlies, and is conformable to the sandstone but is limited in extent. This deposit has had my attention for the last 12 years but never before detected a trace of organic structure. Waiting at this spot for the Bus, to take me to New Town<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hobart.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> the other day, I carelessly cast my eyes upon the formation when to my great delight I discovered the plants in about a square foot but apparently barren elsewhere. On my return while walking to town I accidentally turned up with the toe of my boot a peice of shale containing a splendid specimen of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">odontopteris</hi>
               </seg>. I found I was walking over a rich bed of fossils […] state of one of our […] to ask permission to work at it, when I feel certain I will be able to send you some specimens worth placing in your museum.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I send to your care a small collection of beetles for your friend Count de Castlenau. I do this as I do not know his address.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Apologising my dear Sir for being so troublesome</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Believe me to remain</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your very humble Sert<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Servant.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>S. H. Wintle</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">P.S. Query — Don’t you think I am getting near my <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Calamites">Calamites</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> now? I enclose the specimens in two or three odd slips of my articles from one of our papers<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Enclosures not found. Wintle contributed natural history articles to the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Launceston examiner, </seg>for example Wintle (1868) and Wintle (1868a), and the Hobart <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Mercury</seg> (Wintle (1869)), and also verse<seg style="">, but none of the 1868 or early 1869 articles found deals with the fossil plant, </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Calamites">Calamites</name>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="">.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">SHW</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Calamites">Calamites</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Odontopteris">Odontopteris</name>
            </p>
         </div>
